''Super Smash Bros. Brawl'' has received much critical acclaim thus far. The editors of ''[[Famitsu]]'', who awarded a perfect score,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/845/845816p1.html|title=Perfect Score for Smash Bros.|accessdate=2008-01-29|date=2008-01-16|publisher=[[IGN]]}}</ref> praised the variety and depth of the single-player content, the unpredictability of Final Smashes, and the dynamic fighting styles of the characters.<ref name=Famscore/> Chris Slate of ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' also awarded ''Brawl'' a perfect score in the [[March 2008]] issue, calling it "one of the very best games that Nintendo has ever produced".<ref name=NPBrawl /> ''[[GameSpot]]'' praised the simplicity of the game, noting that "its simple controls and gameplay make it remarkably accessible to beginners yet still appealing to Smash Bros. veterans",<ref name=GameSpotReview>{{Citation | url = http://www.gamespot.com/wii/action/supersmashbros/index.html | title = Gamespot Super Smash Bros. Brawl Review | accessdate = 2008-03-07}}</ref> ''[[GameTrailers]]'' praised the amount of content that gives the game "staying power that few other games possess."<ref name=GameTrailersReview>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/player/31663.html|title=GameTrailers Super Smash Bros. Brawl Review|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref>

''[[IGN]]'' critic [[Matt Casamassina]] noted that although ''Brawl'' is "completely engrossing and wholly entertaining," it suffers from "long loading times" and "uninspired enemies" in the ''Subspace Emissary'' adventure mode. The review also gave a mixed response to the quality of the graphics, and described them as "an enhanced version of ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee|Melee]]''" with improved character models and backgrounds that "lack detail in areas."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.wii.ign.com/articles/856/856580p1.html|title=uk.wii.ign.com/articles/856/856580p1.html<!--INSERT TITLE-->}}</ref> ''[[GameSpy]]'' claimed the graphics look "like the GameCube game."<ref name=GSpyReview>{{Citation | url = http://uk.wii.gamespy.com/wii/super-smash-bros-wii/857904p1.html | title = Super Smash Bros. Brawl review at Gamespy | accessdate = 2008-03-08}}</ref> ''[[NGamer]]'' points to the franchise's lack of innovation with the verdict, "Smash Bros risks growing too familiar. It never breeds contempt, but it doesn't quite muster that ''[[Super Mario Galaxy|Galaxy]]'' magic."<ref name=ngamer />

In Japan, ''Brawl'' sold over 500,000 units on launch day,<ref name="Jeuxvid<U+00E9>o.com">{{cite web|url= http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/2008/00024224-demarrage-canon-pour-super-smash-bros-brawl.htm |title= D<U+00E9>marrage canon pour Super Smash Bros Brawl |accessdate=2008-02-10 |date=2008-02-01 |publisher= jeuxvideo.com}}</ref> 820,000 units in its first week,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nintendo.com/consumer/repair/repair_form_us_ssbb.jsp |title= [[Nintendo]] - [[Customer Service]] ''Super Smash Brawl''|accessdate= 2008-03-10 |date= 2008-03-10
|publisher= [[Kotaku]]}}</ref> and about 1.45 million units total as of [[March 16]], [[2008]].<ref name="japansales">{{cite web|url= http://gonintendo.com/?p=38335 |title= Japanese software sales - March 10th to 16th |accessdate=2008-03-20 |date=2008-03-20 |publisher= GoNintendo}}</ref> In North America, ''Brawl'' sold over 874,000 units on launch day and over 1.4 million units in its first week, making it the fastest selling title in Nintendo of America's history.<ref name="americasales">{{cite web |url=http://press.nintendo.com/articles.jsp?id=14821 |title=Super Smash Bros. Brawl Smashes Nintendo Sales Records |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |date=2008-03-17 |accessdate=2008-03-17}}</ref>
